emic. Drawing on both western and Indigenous methodologies, this unique scholarly contribution takes both a sociological perspective and the "two-eyed seeing" approach to research methods. By looking at the ways that everyday research practices contribute to the colonization of health outcomes for Indigenous peoples, Decolonizing Data exposes the social dimensions of healthcare and offers a careful and respectful reflection on how to "unsettle conversations" about applied social research initiatives for our most vulnerable groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aDecolonizationzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxHealth and hygienezCanada. 0aSocial sciencesxResearchzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Social Theory.2bisacsh  aCanadian landscape.  aIndigenous Peoples.  aIndigenous health.  aallyship.  acolonization.  adecolonization.  areconciliation.  aresearch methods.  aresidential schools.  asocial capital theory.  aurban landscape.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753009940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487530099423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487530099/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles